The error indicates that the remote repository already contains commits that you don't have in your local repository. To resolve this, you can either synchronize your local repository with the remote changes or overwrite the remote repository with your local commits.

Steps to Fix the Issue

Option 1: Pull and Merge Remote Changes

This option integrates remote changes into your local repository before pushing.

  1. Fetch and merge the remote changes:

    bash
    git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories

  2. Resolve any merge conflicts if they occur, then commit the resolved changes:

    bash
    git commit -m "Resolved merge conflicts"

  3. Push the changes to the remote repository:

    bash
    git push -u origin main

Option 2: Force Push to Overwrite Remote Repository

Use this option only if you want to completely replace the remote repository's content with your local changes.

  1. Force push your local branch:
    bash
    git push -u origin main --force

Warning: Force pushing will overwrite all the content in the remote repository with your local changes. Ensure this is what you intend to do.

What to Choose?

  • If you need to preserve any existing files or commits in the remote repository, go with Option 1.
  • If the remote repository has no important files or data that you care about, choose Option 2.
